=E2=80=8B

Let=E2=80=99s begin with a quick introduction.

=E2=80=8B

The main issue and improvement was rendering.

On our old website, we were simply doing client-side rendering.

This means that the server sends the HTML, CSS, and JavaScript
code to the client (the user on their device).

Then the browser executes it, and the page is displayed.

The =E2=80=98new=E2=80=99 approach is Server-Side Rendering. The code is al=
ready
rendered on the server before it is sent to the user. The page
loads faster.

=E2=80=8B

Now, there aren=E2=80=99t just two rendering methodologies.

There are four in total:

* Client-Side Rendering (CSR)
* Server-Side Rendering (SSR)
* Static-Site Generation (SSG)
* Incremental Static Regeneration (ISR)

=E2=80=8B
You=E2=80=99re familiar with CSR.

The difference between SSR and SSG is that SSR renders pages on
the server on every request - while SSG renders it once at build
time and serves it from a CDN, providing the best performance.

=E2=80=8B

When do I use SSR, and when do I use SSG?

-> Use SSR when you need fresh data, and SSG with data that isn=E2=80=99t
updated often (like articles and blog posts).

Let=E2=80=99s not forget ISR if you have a tonne of pages and you don=E2=80=
=99t
want to generate them all at build time.

=E2=80=8B

In our case, we=E2=80=99re using all four rendering methodologies
depending on what=E2=80=99s needed.

=E2=80=8B

Now, let=E2=80=99s put this theory into practice. Imagine a common
scenario:
Implementing a form with Next.js.

=E2=80=8B

You might think to yourself:

=E2=80=9CWell I need the form to be interactive and I need to send data,
so there=E2=80=99s no way it can be rendered on the server side.=E2=80=9D

=E2=80=8B

But, there is a way.

You might have seen the Masterclass admission modal or the
Ultimate Next13 Course waitlist form.

Here=E2=80=99s how it works.

=E2=80=8B

